      "tier2": "Solar panels are made up of many photovoltaic (PV) cells. When sunlight hits these cells, the photons in the light excite electrons in the semiconductor material of the cells. This creates an electrical current, which is then collected and sent to an inverter to convert it into usable AC power for your home or business. The process is based on the photoelectric effect, where light energy knocks electrons loose, creating a flow of electricity.",
      "tier3": "Solar panels work through a process called the photovoltaic effect.  They are composed of numerous photovoltaic cells, typically made of silicon.  Each cell contains two layers of silicon, one doped with phosphorus (n-type) and the other with boron (p-type).  When sunlight strikes the silicon, photons (light particles) transfer their energy to electrons in the silicon atoms. This transfer energizes the electrons, causing them to break free from their atoms.  Because of the different doping of the silicon layers, an electric field is created between the n-type and p-type silicon.  This field directs the freed electrons towards the n-type layer, creating a flow of electrons – an electric current.  This current is then collected by metal contacts on the surface of the cell and channeled to wires, which connect to form a larger array and ultimately to an inverter. The inverter converts the direct current (DC) electricity generated by the solar cells into alternating current (AC) electricity, which is the type used in homes and businesses."
